        {
          "username": "Dandan Yang",
          "rating": 1,
          "contributor_id": "114326947856307910301",
          "user_review_count": 5,
          "user_photo_count": 7,
          "user_thumbnail": "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a/ACg8ocL8-Mv4fwIrTkKtdAxntLebG8NzoZepLGjl5e4y9qnlt3SDRVM=s120-c-rp-mo-ba12-br100",
          "description": "We had a deeply concerning experience at NewYork-Presbyterian Lower Manhattan Hospital on March 16, 2026, involving interpreter services.\n\nDuring a critical situation related to a psychiatric transfer, the assigned interpreter (Chris Lu) did not act as a neutral translator. Instead, the interpreter actively interfered with communication between our family and the doctor.\n\nWe were prevented from asking questions, blocked from requesting a written medical evaluation, and the interpreter discouraged the doctor from providing explanations. When we attempted to speak, we were threatened with security removal.\n\nThis conduct significantly impacted our ability to understand and participate in an important medical decision. In a healthcare setting, especially during psychiatric evaluation and transfer, clear and unbiased communication is essential.\n\nWe have formally reported this incident. We strongly urge the hospital to review interpreter conduct and ensure that language access services are professional, neutral, and do not interfere with patient rights.",
          "link": "https://www.google.com/maps/reviews/data=!4m8!14m7!1m6!2m5!1sCi9DQUlRQUNvZENodHljRjlvT2podE4xTlFTWGhDVjA0elExRllSRVZRZHpSTmIxRRAB!2m1!1s0x0:0x92da9e7eb069aebf!3m1!1s2@1:CAIQACodChtycF9oOjhtN1NQSXhCV04zQ1FYREVQdzRNb1E%7C%7C?hl=en",
